<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="224" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,618,1620]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,690,715]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" box="[618,793,690,715]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subcucullata">
<emphasis box="[618,793,690,715]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">P. subcucullata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to those of 
<emphasis box="[1078,1246,690,715]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName authority="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho, 2019" authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" box="[1078,1243,690,715]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drepanodes" status="sp. nov.">P. drepanodes</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1258,1352,690,715]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1258,1352,690,715]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicName authority="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho, 2019" authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassiella" status="sp. nov.">P. crassiella</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[277,370,726,751]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[277,370,726,751]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, with a similar signum, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" box="[706,880,726,751]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subcucullata">
<emphasis box="[706,880,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">P. subcucullata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those species by the caudal margin of the abdominal segment VIII, which is incised medially with a V-shaped emargination, compared to the deeply emarginated into a U-shape in the latter two species, and by the large, heavily sclerotized plate in the posterior of ductus bursae. This new species can be distinguished from other morphologically similar species known only from males as follows: 1) from 
<taxonomicName authority="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho, 2019" authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" box="[645,741,870,895]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[645,741,870,895]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">P. pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[748,838,870,895]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[748,838,870,895]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho, 2019" authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" box="[892,1002,870,895]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hylodes" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[892,1002,870,895]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">P. hylodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1012,1102,870,895]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1012,1102,870,895]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by the transversely elongated antemedian fascia on the forewing; and 2) from 
<taxonomicName authority="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho, 2019" authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" box="[686,822,906,931]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vokaensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[686,822,906,931]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">P. vokaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,917,906,931]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[828,917,906,931]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by the absence of a white hyaline patch on the hind wing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="224" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,618,1620]" box="[199,915,978,1003]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,978,1003]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Description.</emphasis>
Female (
<figureCitation box="[449,538,978,1003]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1029,1051]" captionTargetBox="[160,1429,211,997]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1435,193,1008]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 15. Ptilothyris subcucullata Park. A, Holotype, female, in CMP; B, Labels of holotype; C, Antenna; D, Female genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-6849; D, Signum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594887/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Figs. 15</figureCitation>
A–C). Forewing length 10.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,618,1620]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis box="[199,260,1014,1039]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Head</emphasis>
: Vertex purplish dark fuscous; greyish orange erect scales laterally, arising from upper margin of compound eye. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[450,553,1050,1075]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1029,1051]" captionTargetBox="[160,1429,211,997]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1435,193,1008]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 15. Ptilothyris subcucullata Park. A, Holotype, female, in CMP; B, Labels of holotype; C, Antenna; D, Female genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-6849; D, Signum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594887/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Fig. 15C</figureCitation>
) shorter than forewing, biserrate, purplish dark fuscous for basal ¾, orange white for the rest, with black spot at apex. Second segment of labial palpus thickened, brownish orange intermixed with dark fuscous scales on dorsal and outer surface, with pale greyish orange apex, pale orange on inner surface; 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[165,178,1157,1171]" fontSize="6" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">rd</superScript>
segment slender, as long as 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[506,522,1157,1171]" fontSize="6" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">nd</superScript>
segment, nearly right angle to second segment, orange white dorsally, dark brown ventrally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,618,1620]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis box="[199,280,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Thorax</emphasis>
: Notum and tegula purplish dark fuscous. Forewing purplish fuscous, with dark-brown scales scattered for apical 1/3; costa nearly straight, arched in apical ¼; apex obtuse; termen slightly oblique; fringe concolorous, with narrow indistinct orange-white basal line; venation with M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[876,884,1319,1333]" fontSize="6" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">1</subScript>
free. Hind wing similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho, 2019" authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" box="[1194,1436,1304,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leifaarviki" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1194,1436,1304,1329]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Ptilothyris leifaarviki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,240,1343,1368]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,240,1343,1368]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,618,1620]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1379,1404]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[523,668,1379,1404]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1029,1051]" captionTargetBox="[160,1429,211,997]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1435,193,1008]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 15. Ptilothyris subcucullata Park. A, Holotype, female, in CMP; B, Labels of holotype; C, Antenna; D, Female genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-6849; D, Signum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594887/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Figs. 15D, E</figureCitation>
) with abdominal sternite VIII deeply emarginated medially. Ostium bursae more narrowly emarginated, extending past middle of antrum. Apophyses anteriores broken. Antrum large, sclerotized, nearly quadrate. Ductus bursae broadened, longer than corpus bursae, sclerotized in posterior 1/3, with heavily sclerotized, elongate longitudinal plate. Corpus bursae ovate; signum is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Park &amp; Mey &amp; Koo &amp; Prins &amp; Cho" authorityYear="2019" box="[1239,1382,1487,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leifaarviki">
<emphasis box="[1239,1382,1487,1512]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">P. leifaarviki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,483,1523,1548]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" type="distribution">
